üßÆ Official Distribution of Preventive Measures
(as presented in public health sources, checked by Copilot)

| Domain                       | Preventive Method                  | Estimated Contribution |
|------------------------------|------------------------------------|------------------------|
| Medical Prophylaxis          | Vaccination                        | 20%                    |
|                              | Regular medical screening          | 15%                    |
| Healthy Lifestyle            | Balanced nutrition                 | 15%                    |
|                              | Physical activity                  | 10%                    |
|                              | Sleep and rest                     | 5%                     |
| Hygiene and Physical Safety  | Personal and public hygiene        | 10%                    |
|                              | Smoking cessation                  | 5%                     |
| Mental Health                | Stress management                  | 5%                     |
| Education and Awareness      | Health education and information   | 2%                     |
| Other Measures               | Miscellaneous                      | 13%                    |
|------------------------------|------------------------------------|------------------------|
| **TOTAL**                    |                                    | **100%**               |

The official table belongs to an earlier generation of prevention ‚Äî a generation built on linear templates, uniform procedures, and the 
assumption that people can be guided through identical steps. It reflects a time when standardization was considered efficiency, and 
individuality was treated as noise. The table is not wrong; it is simply limited. It cannot account for personal evolution, for 
complexity, for the dynamic nature of real life. It offers structure, but not adaptability. It organizes information, but it does not 
develop the person.
From this point forward, we move beyond the table. Not to dismiss it, but to surpass it ‚Äî to replace linear templates with personal 
growth, uniform steps with multidimensional development, and rigid procedures with a living, adaptive process of prophylaxis.

